'above' > 1, 'below' < 1. * Collisions: hash func output collisions, not index. * Might not matter much at low rates if used only for indexing into the table like here in these tests -- depends on how you're resolving it in your hash table. * Note: currently the collision map takes into account only 4 lo bytes of output, that's where the high number of collisions might be coming from in the first place. Maybe. * Native 4-byte hash funcs demonstrate their superiority here. * t1ha is of a particular interest, as despite not being 4-byte native func, it has better distribution. * Also there are exactly 9 dups in dic_ip. * 'above' and 'below': buckets filled up above and below perfect 100% respectively. * 'ok': buckets filled up to the perfect 100%. * 'zero': buckets with no entries. * '<%' and '>%': number of buckets going below and above some %, so 25% < N <= 50%. * Less than 25% will ***not*** put you in less than 50%, etc. There is no <% 0, see 'zero' instead. ### Sanity / simple example
